At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German project under which the legislation on public procurement in these two countries was compared.
What was the real issue?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how public procurement and specific national legislation are managed, as well as the practice itself.
We have gathered all this and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more severe and of better quality", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not sufficient to continuously develop increasingly detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote itself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what is the result for you?
Common control of this kind should contribute precisely to our stopping efforts to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a truly positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the matter at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering market thresholds, we will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so submerged by paperwork that those seeking fault will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
