Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it was the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had been working closely with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always find understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw astronomical observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astroutics ".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld earned in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his work "Introduction à l'astroutique".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned astronomical propagator, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
From 1925 it was built in Poland a root for use with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the root.
The only known information on this root is that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the records that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research has ceased.
In 1937, the plans of a photo-hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
The purpose of these two projects was military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Committee and Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works dedicated to aviation were published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronomical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronomy
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the area of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and as of autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the international astronomical federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 metres was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was constructed, RM-1A and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-storey RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metre long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965 succeeds in the first MRI-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (known as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed and distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all types of equipment was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, and the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national committee COSPAR two years later should be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and in 1978 the Miroslaw Hermaszewski pilot became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
