The film Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a number of demonstrators made up of Islamic students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome, and it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously disturbed the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate is a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian feeling in the United States.
The Iranian Debacle contributed heavily to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated peripeties, they found themselves in the residence of the ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team that came to make screenings for the shooting of a major science-fiction film.
Gender Combination
The exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is on the one hand a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful hit, a betrayal - such as in the trilogy Ocean's elevent, twelve and tirteen.
The ambiances succeed: sequences of Teheran of documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photographs, these same situations have been retransscribed in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with men dressed up discussing the situation around conference tables, corridors and telephone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting game stopped raising ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark police officer " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his home town, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests the confusion and unpredictableness when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many locations
The director had to be content with a subject that actually offered only a few palpitating scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It goes well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is driven away by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track is sufficiently fired by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated nature, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperatives, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of yet another history, in a certain way unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the matter.
