The architects of the MVRDV cabinet prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince themselves, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it makes it very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the bottom of the street, tells us.
Stefan Spermon, a computerist in a large neighbouring company, tells us, "Yes, he's really nice, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes any further than that in one of these wide-ranging libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the doors of Rotterdam, holds a quite special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back to the statistics: building a library!
Winy Maas, from Rotterdam MVRDV's architect's office, master of bold and spirit-filled building diagrams, accepted the project with its usual flexage and presented in 2003 with five books under his arm and a wink on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking, puzzled and lifting their shoulders, Maas, the confronted, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his discourse backed up by activist arguments by one: "common auction!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as we say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros fell to the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project including an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
Early in November, the mountain of books received the second award "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small, tender village, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a city hall of an aghast laideur, whose white facades invite to think that they shelter a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you crowd the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant verbs speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Usually, library beams are located along the facade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," Willy Maas explains.
We have completely overturned the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been properly furnished: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the building's technical center.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes of the slabs, sometimes of the balustrades, sometimes of the stairway ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in an agricultural company ad hoc waste comes from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, the synthetic membrane of one millimeter thick has been used for years as substrate in the greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we get time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
Top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 metres, the literary coffee offers a stunning view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and figus pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of moisture in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project on ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is adjusted by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even the days of good time.
The beam thickness of wood mounted across the glass facade serves as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated stores are loaded with the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" by Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure helped to fill the gaps in the library that were not yet fully garnished (currently, it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master's discipline, which is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain when voting on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution because it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without being overly critical of Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain when voting on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Furthermore, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are therefore facing several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still trying to find this role, but they're on the path to a "more normal" foreign policy.
An external policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position towards the Middle East conflict and the abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to undermine public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a key element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a key element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain from important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration shows a secret understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem to be.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelmingly enthusiastic about Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany experience difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore join a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing now in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, particularly because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been sensitive.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that marks their independence more.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable for it and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking, for example, at the euro crisis, it is noted that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for Germans.
In fact, this is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at this point the EU does not fill this gap, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them, and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Protection of brands" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands all over the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys protection such that the company that bears the name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd get a cause.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, lawyer at Taylor Wessing's firm specializing in violation of the property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators need only a few additional letters in order to record their marks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies have also been legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports items.
Pattloch opens a binder where registrations are made with the Beijing Trademarks Office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company filed the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by appropriate part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become champions of the world of copying and violation of intellectual property.
