For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gas emanating from the entrances of the earth solidifies to the contact of the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh almost 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
It's only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to gravitate this distance, at a tortoise, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen minors earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once up, he breaks a path between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying painfully heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has installed a little under 1,850 meters of altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, you can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents euros) per kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 cents euros) to the petrochemical industry as this ore is very present in daily life and is used to manufacture candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and is exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what it would gain in the fields.
