It may seem imaginable that these words come from an advertising for mint pills, but despite this, or perhaps thanks to this, the video has spread like a dust trail on YouTube in Singapore at the beginning of this year.
The words come from a rap group that uses local references such as "Allon put a polykine in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency at the origin of the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way thanks to this advertising.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to "their national duty".
It is intended only for the Internet, so we have been able to make it fun and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the area of birth, so we felt that it was a theme we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things like throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of these ideas were creative but they did not necessarily work.
So we said the following: what is more creative to solve this problem than to make a rap song?
1.2 children
The Government of Singapore does not take that lightly.
It spends US$1,300 a year in politics to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure for marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, in line with its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered to be the rate of renewal, it was in 1976.
Why, then, do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Division, says it is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have a wider range of options in terms of goals of life and priorities, beyond marriage and the creation of a family," she explains.
These changes in social standards have contributed to an increase in the number of unmarried people and delay marriage and birth, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the decline of the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that are simply disguised into xenophobia against new immigrants, particularly Chinese people who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore has experienced last year its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this began to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe box", which can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters from wanting to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the EL Developers real estate company, claims that its "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger housing.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than those larger.
For this reason, it is much more cost-effective for our cash.
However, he admits that the new standards provide clearer guidance to promoters, who were previously put on wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a state city.
If these new regulations could be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, discussing with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the centre, it would appear that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that's why people give it back later," says a young manager.
Other people may have children.
"But for me, it's important to be able to have my money and my time," another youth in about twenty years tells us.
Men and women mention their career, stress and cost of access to property and education as the reasons why they prevent them from having children.
Thus, although the government tries to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
