The summit of Unasur ended without the release of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the fact that the Lima Declaration was made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Ephe tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the close of the summit and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When they were questioned about the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
The access of journalists to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The limited information circulated among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of the presidents present, which caused some malaise among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media calling for more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the third Arab South American Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press on an urgent basis, it had also not circulated the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to establish safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the availability of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment by the Hague Court which sets a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the arguments of both parties in the trial Lima tried against Santiago and which begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
"Chili has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," President Piñera added by handing President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit itself to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read out the outcome document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of residence permits agreements".
He reported that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve drug accessibility, low-priced Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our people," concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, particularly in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador although it did not provide further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow for its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and in good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos stated, before the regional meeting began, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with Nicaragua," he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible," said President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they plan to attend the takeover of power of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the Ministers of Defence of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
