Hector "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is my whole life"
The world-troctor of the "Hetin" Reyes basketball has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, has traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have knowledge of the history of local basketball as large as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemns him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
"The basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his route without standards, testify.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s to 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or team manager.
"This was my best years, the ones I enjoyed most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a great deal of satisfaction for many years, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the team of the BSN.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a Costa Rican player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy began, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another one.
He welcomed the Vaqueros Championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manateu of the federation.
At the time, he preferred to take advantage of his duties and those of Mincy on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the Pre-Olympic Tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us play the last game, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the Cuban Pan-American Games in 1991, when we won the gold and we put a hold on the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that had won the bronze during the World.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 due to a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the Pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner in place of players suspended by the Imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all the predictions.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
This is undoubtedly Piculín Ortiz.
Its international tournament statistics are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Piculín did.
And this does not take into account his path in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious period of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the NSA had up to 17 teams in one season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have wanted to put in place, such as regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys only play in their area and face only teams from other parts of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and referees.
That makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch videos from my time on YouTube, I enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, I attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), became known worldwide for the role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied a businessman without scruples, fearless and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as an unscrupulous oil magnet J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year to J.R's role in a new "Dallas" season, died Friday evening from complications of cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved most," said the family.
Larry's family and his close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played her wife's role in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press deputy, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived his whole life," Gray said in a statement.
The doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis in Larry Hagman in 1992 and had acknowledged that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was detected with a malignant tumor in his liver and had a graft.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman was introduced to television in the role of an ordinary type in the "Jinny of My Dreams" series broadcast by the NBC channel from 1965 to 1970.
In it he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two comedies that remained short in the antenna, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Amongst his roles in cinema are roles well received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his master's interpretation of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The drama series of the CBS channel on the Ewing clan and its neighbours was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspension around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman was almost murdered, generated speculations around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
As a result, among other things, the series reached a record of hearings at that time.
When the answer was revealed in an episode of November 1980, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful wife who tried to internalize her alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what should be as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write: "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
Here's the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a "great man, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans throughout the world, and in the heart of each one of us, who had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
Five episodes have already been recorded for the second season and a sixth is being completed, the chain has been informed.
For the time being, neither Warner nor the TNT channel have reported how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
