A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammock: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar on December 21, which many refer to as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what expected him in the following months: Hurricane Hurricane Sandy, a tax gulf that some called the "Debate Army" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists at the end of the time thought the apocalypse would start.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were talking about it, it was a very good time.
And remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker holds the "Media, Culture and the End of the World" course.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could explode.
This month, students will analyze movies with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, the Professor of History of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Assistant Professor of History of Art and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply called "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "near disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the State of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be on the eve of Revelation, which leaves students no choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
Courses have proved to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the start of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursing, claims to have seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, and even less a teacher, told us to believe at the end of the world of December 21.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and we somehow discredited it," says Julie zegle, a senior student from the last year in Temple, aged 21 and from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it is only a key date on the calendar," said Restall.
But I agree that there is anxiety related to apocalypse in Western culture, dating back to several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked such speculation.
"In other places on the globe, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that "the end of the world" was being taught here.
"The Philippines does not participate at the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a superior authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he states that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately begin to think about the next date" or philosopher about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Several told us they were planning to go to "end of the world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together," commented Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
